          "text": "Analyze the following review for @ROADMAP.md and @WHITEPAPER.md and it's implications:\n\n```\n1. Forward secrecy claim vs. reality (§3.3 vs §7.1)\nYour security goals in §3.3 list forward secrecy as goal #4, but §7.1 and §12.3 openly admit MIK-only has no forward secrecy. This isn't impossible — it's contradictory. A compromised MIK exposes every past and future message encrypted to it. You acknowledge this, but listing it as a security goal you currently meet is misleading. The honest framing would be: \"forward secrecy is a v1.0 goal, not a v0.x property.\"\n2. Deniability claim is questionable (§3.3, goal #6)\nYou claim repudiation/deniability, but your XEdDSA signature in the InnerEnvelope is bound to the sender's long-term MIK. If Alice sends Bob a message, Bob holds a signature verifiable against Alice's public key. A third party who obtains Bob's decrypted InnerEnvelope can verify that signature against Alice's PublicID. This is not deniable in the way Signal achieves deniability (where MAC keys are revealed, making forgery possible). Your current design provides authentication, not deniability. You'd need something like a ring signature or a shared MAC-based approach to get real deniability.\n3. 8-byte ContentId collision risk (§9.1)\nYou say 8 bytes gives ~4 billion messages before birthday collision. That's not quite right. Birthday bound on 64 bits is ~2³² ≈ 4.3 billion, yes, but that's the 50% collision probability. At scale — say a heavily-used group chat post-v1.0 with thousands of participants — you could hit collisions much sooner. A ContentId collision in the DAG would cause incorrect gap detection, phantom \"missing messages,\" or silent message loss. For a 1:1 chat this is fine. For future group messaging with high throughput, 8 bytes is dangerously tight. Consider 16 bytes, or at least document the group-messaging collision risk explicitly.\n4. Async Noise XX without prekey servers is hard, not impossible (§7.4, §14.1)\nYour v1.0 plan says \"Noise XX session establishment (no prekey servers)\" where \"either party can initiate.\" This is achievable but has a subtle problem in DTN: both parties might simultaneously initiate a handshake while disconnected, creating crossed handshakes. You need a deterministic role assignment (you mention this briefly), but the details matter enormously. If both Alice and Bob initiate Noise XX to each other while offline, you get two independent sessions. Your DAG could help resolve this (the first acknowledged session wins), but you need to spec this conflict resolution carefully or you'll get split-brain session states.\n5. RSSI-based relay timing for BLE (§v0.10) — physically unreliable\nRSSI is notoriously noisy indoors: multipath, body absorption, and orientation cause ±20 dB variance. Meshtastic gets away with this on LoRa because LoRa operates at lower frequencies with more predictable propagation. BLE at 2.4 GHz in indoor environments will produce near-random RSSI ordering. This won't be \"impossible\" but it'll be unreliable enough that your duplicate suppression will frequently misfire. You'll want a randomized backoff with RSSI as a hint, not a deterministic timer.\n6. QR code for ~500 byte messages (§v0.5)\nYour OuterEnvelope overhead is ~73 bytes, InnerEnvelope minimum ~107 bytes, plus Poly1305 tag. A minimal text message is ~180-220 bytes. Base64-encoded for QR, that's ~240-300 characters. A standard QR code handles this fine (Version 10 QR holds ~652 alphanumeric chars). But 500 bytes of content plus envelope overhead would be ~680+ bytes → ~900+ Base64 characters → needs Version 18+ QR code, which is hard to scan reliably from phone cameras at distance. This is feasible but you should set expectations: QR works for short messages only. Binary QR mode would help.\n7. Single-key identity is a real tradeoff (§6.1)\nUsing the same X25519 key for both ECDH and signatures (via XEdDSA) is convenient but means compromising one function compromises both. If an attacker gets your signing key, they also get your decryption key. Most modern protocols separate these (Signal has identity key + signed prekey + one-time prekeys). You're aware of this, but the \"simplified backup\" benefit should be weighed against the blast radius of a single key compromise. Not impossible, just a deliberate single point of failure.\n8. LoRa MTU and realistic message sizes (§11.3)\nYou mention ~200 byte LoRa MTU and transport-layer chunking in v0.7. Meshtastic's practical payload per packet is more like 228 bytes with their headers, but duty cycle regulations (especially in EU at 868 MHz) limit you to ~1% airtime. A 3-chunk message on EU LoRa could take 5-10 minutes to transmit with legal duty cycle compliance. This isn't impossible but it means multi-chunk messages over Meshtastic will be very slow. Your users need to understand \"LoRa messaging\" means \"short texts with minutes of latency.\"\n9. Routing key privacy is weaker than described (§5.3)\nYou say the routing key \"cannot be reversed to PublicID\" — true, but it's a deterministic function of PublicID. Anyone who knows a target's PublicID can compute their routing key and monitor which mailboxes they poll. This is fine for your threat model (relay nodes are semi-trusted), but the privacy property is \"routing key hides identity from nodes that don't already know you,\" not \"routing key provides anonymity.\" Worth being precise here.\n10. No message padding until v1.0 (§12.6)\nWithout padding, message length reveals content type and approximate text length to any relay or network observer. Combined with the stable routing key, this enables \"Alice sent Bob a 47-byte message at 3 PM\" fingerprinting. This is a known limitation you've documented, but it's worth noting that for your adversarial target scenarios (authoritarian regimes, §1), this is a meaningful gap until v1.0.\n```",
